        <!-- Section 1: How a Case Moves Through the Courts -->
        <section id="case-path" class="mb-16">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center mb-2 font-lora reveal" data-key="section1_title">How a Case Moves Through the Courts</h2>
            <p class="text-center text-gray-600 mb-12 max-w-2xl mx-auto reveal" data-key="section1_subtitle">Think of the court system as a set of steps. Click each step to learn more.</p>
            
            <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-8 items-start reveal">
                <!-- Interactive Stepper -->
                <div class="w-full md:w-1/3">
                    <div class="relative">
                        <!-- Connecting Line -->
                        <div class="absolute left-5 top-0 w-0.5 bg-gray-300 step-line"></div>
                        
                        <div class="step-item relative mb-8 pl-12 cursor-pointer" data-step="1"><div class="step-circle absolute left-0 top-0 w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-white border-2 border-gray-300 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg text-gray-500 transition-all duration-300">1</div><h3 class="step-title pt-2 text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 transition-colors duration-300" data-key="step1_title">Trial Court</h3></div>
                        <div class="step-item relative mb-8 pl-12 cursor-pointer" data-step="2"><div class="step-circle absolute left-0 top-0 w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-white border-2 border-gray-300 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg text-gray-500 transition-all duration-300">2</div><h3 class="step-title pt-2 text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 transition-colors duration-300" data-key="step2_title">Appeals Court</h3></div>
                        <div class="step-item relative mb-8 pl-12 cursor-pointer" data-step="3"><div class="step-circle absolute left-0 top-0 w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-white border-2 border-gray-300 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg text-gray-500 transition-all duration-300">3</div><h3 class="step-title pt-2 text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 transition-colors duration-300" data-key="step3_title">State Supreme Court</h3></div>
                        <div class="step-item relative pl-12 cursor-pointer" data-step="4"><div class="step-circle absolute left-0 top-0 w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-white border-2 border-gray-300 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg text-gray-500 transition-all duration-300"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-6 w-6" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M3 10h18M3 14h18m-9-4v8m-7 0h14a2 2 0 002-2V8a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v8a2 2 0 002 2z" /></svg></div><h3 class="step-title pt-2 text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 transition-colors duration-300" data-key="step4_title">U.S. Supreme Court</h3></div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Content Display -->
                <div class="w-full md:w-2/3">
                    <div id="step-1-content" class="content-card bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg border border-gray-200"><h4 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" data-key="step1_content_title">Trial Court (First Step)</h4><ul class="space-y-3 list-disc list-inside text-gray-700"><li data-key="step1_bullet1">This is where the case begins.</li><li data-key="step1_bullet2">A judge (and sometimes a jury) looks at the facts: What actually happened? Who broke the law or who is responsible?</li><li data-key="step1_bullet3"><strong>Example:</strong> If someone is accused of stealing, this is where witnesses testify and evidence is shown.</li></ul></div>
                    <div id="step-2-content" class="content-card bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg border border-gray-200"><h4 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" data-key="step2_content_title">Appeals Court (Second Step)</h4><ul class="space-y-3 list-disc list-inside text-gray-700"><li data-key="step2_bullet1">If one side believes the trial was unfair or the judge made a legal mistake, they can “appeal.”</li><li data-key="step2_bullet2">Appeals courts don’t re-do the trial. Instead, they ask: Did the trial follow the correct rules of law?</li></ul></div>
                    <div id="step-3-content" class="content-card bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg border border-gray-200"><h4 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" data-key="step3_content_title">State Supreme Court (Third Step)</h4><ul class="space-y-3 list-disc list-inside text-gray-700"><li data-key="step3_bullet1">The highest court in a state.</li><li data-key="step3_bullet2">If the issue only involves state law, this is usually the end of the road.</li></ul></div>
                    <div id="step-4-content" class="content-card bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg border border-gray-200"><h4 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" data-key="step4_content_title">U.S. Supreme Court (Final Step)</h4><ul class="space-y-3 list-disc list-inside text-gray-700"><li data-key="step4_bullet1">The Supreme Court only takes a very small number of cases each year (around 70–80).</li><li data-key="step4_bullet2">They choose cases that involve the U.S. Constitution or important national issues that affect everyone.</li></ul></div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Other Sections Grid -->
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8 mb-16">
            <div class="info-card reveal bg-blue-50 p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 transition-all duration-300"><h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-800 mb-4 font-lora" data-key="section2_title">What the Supreme Court Does</h3><p class="mb-4" data-key="section2_p1">The Supreme Court does not retry cases or hear new witnesses.</p><p data-key="section2_p2">Instead, it decides big questions like:</p><ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 space-y-2 text-blue-900"><li data-key="section2_bullet1">Does this law follow the <span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="constitution">Constitution</span>?</li><li data-key="section2_bullet2">Does this government action respect people’s rights?</li></ul></div>
            <div class="info-card reveal bg-yellow-50 p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 transition-all duration-300"><h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-yellow-800 mb-4 font-lora" data-key="section3_title">Precedent & Stare Decisis</h3><p class="mb-2"><strong class="font-semibold"><span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="precedent">Precedent</span>:</strong> <span data-key="section3_def1">“what was decided before.”</span></p><p class="mb-4"><strong class="font-semibold"><span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="stare_decisis">Stare Decisis</span>:</strong> <span data-key="section3_def2">A Latin phrase meaning “let the decision stand.”</span></p><p class="text-sm text-yellow-900" data-key="section3_p1">The idea is to keep law stable, but the Court can <span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="overturn">overturn</span> precedent.</p></div>
            <div class="info-card reveal bg-green-50 p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 transition-all duration-300"><h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-green-800 mb-4 font-lora" data-key="section5_title">Why This Matters</h3><p class="mb-4" data-key="section5_p1">Decisions can change everyday life for millions. Key examples:</p><ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-green-900"><li><span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="brown_v_board">Brown v. Board of Education</span></li><li><span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="miranda_v_arizona">Miranda v. Arizona</span></li></ul></div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Section 4 & 6: Accordion Sections -->
        <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-16">
            <!-- Section 4: How the Court Analyzes a Case -->
            <div class="bg-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg border border-gray-200 reveal">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6 text-center font-lora" data-key="section4_title">How the Supreme Court Analyzes a Case</h3>
                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <div class="accordion-item border-b border-gray-200 pb-3"><div class="accordion-header cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center"><h4 class="text-lg font-semibold" data-key="section4_step1_title">1. Identify the Constitutional Question</h4><div class="accordion-icon text-blue-500 text-3xl font-light">+</div></div><div class="accordion-content text-gray-600" data-key="section4_step1_desc">Which part of the Constitution is being challenged? Is it about free speech, equal protection, or the right to privacy?</div></div>
                    <div class="accordion-item border-b border-gray-200 pb-3"><div class="accordion-header cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center"><h4 class="text-lg font-semibold" data-key="section4_step2_title">2. Review Precedent</h4><div class="accordion-icon text-blue-500 text-3xl font-light">+</div></div><div class="accordion-content text-gray-600" data-key="section4_step2_desc">Have similar cases been decided before? Does the precedent support one side, or should it be reconsidered?</div></div>
                    <div class="accordion-item border-b border-gray-200 pb-3"><div class="accordion-header cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center"><h4 class="text-lg font-semibold" data-key="section4_step3_title">3. Hear Arguments & Write Opinions</h4><div class="accordion-icon text-blue-500 text-3xl font-light">+</div></div><div class="accordion-content text-gray-600"><p data-key="section4_step3_desc">Lawyers argue, justices debate privately, then they write a <span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="majority_opinion">Majority Opinion</span>, and sometimes <span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="concurring_opinion">Concurring</span> or <span class="interactive-term" data-modal-key="dissenting_opinion">Dissenting Opinions</span>.</p></div></div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Section 6: How to Evaluate a Case -->
            <div class="bg-gray-800 text-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg reveal">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6 text-center font-lora" data-key="section6_title">How to Evaluate a Supreme Court Case</h3>
                <p class="text-center text-gray-300 mb-6" data-key="section6_subtitle">Click each question to see what to look for:</p>
                <div class="space-y-4">
                    <div class="accordion-item bg-gray-700 rounded-lg">
                        <div class="accordion-header cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-4">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold" data-key="section6_q1_title">1. What is the constitutional issue?</h4>
                            <div class="accordion-icon text-gray-400 text-3xl font-light">+</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content text-gray-300 px-4" data-key="section6_q1_desc">Pinpoint the exact part of the Constitution in question. Is it the First Amendment's guarantee of free speech? The Fourteenth Amendment's promise of "equal protection"? Naming the specific right or clause is the first step.</div>
                    </div>
                     <div class="accordion-item bg-gray-700 rounded-lg">
                        <div class="accordion-header cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-4">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold" data-key="section6_q2_title">2. What precedent exists?</h4>
                            <div class="accordion-icon text-gray-400 text-3xl font-light">+</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content text-gray-300 px-4" data-key="section6_q2_desc">How have courts ruled on this issue before? Did the Court follow, ignore, or overturn previous decisions? Mentioning past cases shows you understand that law is a conversation over time.</div>
                    </div>
                     <div class="accordion-item bg-gray-700 rounded-lg">
                        <div class="accordion-header cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-4">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold" data-key="section6_q3_title">3. How did the justices argue?</h4>
                            <div class="accordion-icon text-gray-400 text-3xl font-light">+</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content text-gray-300 px-4" data-key="section6_q3_desc">Don't just state who won. Explore the *reasoning*. What was the core logic of the majority opinion? What powerful arguments did the dissenting justices make? A strong dissent can influence future law.</div>
                    </div>
                     <div class="accordion-item bg-gray-700 rounded-lg">
                        <div class="accordion-header cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-4">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold" data-key="section6_q4_title">4. What is the impact?</h4>
                            <div class="accordion-icon text-gray-400 text-3xl font-light">+</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content text-gray-300 px-4" data-key="section6_q4_desc">This is the "so what?" question. How did this ruling change the law or affect the rights of ordinary people? Think about the real-world consequences beyond the courtroom.</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Big Idea -->
        <div class="bg-blue-600 text-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg flex items-center justify-center text-center reveal">
            <p class="text-xl font-bold">✨ <span data-key="big_idea">Big Idea: The Supreme Court is not about re-deciding facts. It’s about interpreting the Constitution.</span></p>
        </div>
